"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Job chapters 22–26
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-job-22-26.py

Ch 22 (30v): Eliphaz's third speech — the penitential-restoration offer as shadow of
    the gospel (vv21-30: peace with God, prayer heard, decree established); the social
    crimes catalog (vv6-9) as foil to Christ's actual works of justice (Luke 4:18-19);
    v14's divine hiddenness answered by the Incarnation (John 1:14).
Ch 23 (17v): Job's search for God — John 14:6 as the answer to v3's longing;
    the heavenly mediator who argues the case (Heb 9:24); divine unchangeability
    and Heb 13:8; gold-refining trial and 1 Pet 1:6-7.
Ch 24 (25v): Job's indictment of providence — the eschatological reversal; the cry
    of the wounded answered (Luke 18:7-8); light-haters and John 3:19-20;
    the dawn rising answered by resurrection.
Ch 25 (6v): Bildad's worm question — Rom 3:21-22 answers v4; Ps 22:6 / Col 1:15
    for the worm-to-firstborn typology.
Ch 26 (14v): Job's cosmic hymn — Col 1:17 (all things hold together in Christ) for v7;
    Col 2:15 (triumphing over the serpent) for v13; 1 Cor 2:9 for v14 (outer fringes).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Eliphaz&rsquo;s third speech is the most directly accusatory in the book. As the theological accuser, Eliphaz occupies the structural role of the adversary in the divine council (1:6&ndash;12): both challenge the reality of Job&rsquo;s righteousness. In the NT, the adversary&rsquo;s accusation finds its ultimate answer in Christ&rsquo;s atoning work: Rev 12:10 (&ldquo;the accuser of our brothers has been thrown down, who accuses them before our God day and night&rdquo;) names the overthrown adversary, and v11 (&ldquo;they have conquered him by the blood of the Lamb&rdquo;) names the mechanism of victory. Eliphaz&rsquo;s accusations against Job are structurally the false accusations that Christ&rsquo;s blood permanently defeats.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The question &ldquo;can a man be profitable to God?&rdquo; probes the transactional foundation of religion. The NT answer is not that humans are profitable to God, but that God in Christ makes humans &ldquo;acceptable&rdquo; to himself: Eph 1:6 (&ldquo;to the praise of his glorious grace, with which he has blessed us in the Beloved&rdquo;). The value humans have before God is not intrinsic (Eliphaz is right about this) but derivative &mdash; the value Christ imparts through union. In Christ, the unprofitable servant becomes the adopted son.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Is it any pleasure to the Almighty if you are in the right?&rdquo; &mdash; the question of divine pleasure in human righteousness is answered definitively in Christ: Matt 3:17 (&ldquo;this is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased&rdquo;); 17:5 (the same at the Transfiguration). The Father&rsquo;s pleasure in the Son is the prototype and ground of his pleasure in those united to the Son. Eliphaz is asking the right question without access to the christological answer: the Almighty&rsquo;s pleasure in human righteousness is mediated through his pleasure in Christ.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The ironic question &mdash; is it because of your piety that God reproves you? &mdash; creates the exact structure of the prologue: God&rsquo;s acknowledgment of Job&rsquo;s piety (1:8) leading to his permission of the test. Eliphaz uses the question satirically; the prologue uses it seriously. In the NT, Jesus is similarly tested: Luke 4:1&ndash;13 (the temptation immediately follows the divine declaration of pleasure in 3:22). The beloved Son in whom the Father is well pleased is also the one immediately tested in the wilderness.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Is not your wickedness great? There is no end to your iniquities&rdquo; &mdash; Eliphaz applies to Job the charge that belongs to sinners generally. Isa 53:12: Christ &ldquo;was numbered with the transgressors&rdquo; &mdash; the innocent one bearing the transgressors&rsquo; accusation. Eliphaz voices the false accusation that the cross takes seriously at its deepest level: the sin was not Job&rsquo;s, but Christ genuinely bore what was not his (2 Cor 5:21: &ldquo;he made him to be sin who knew no sin&rdquo;). The accusation that misidentifies the guilty party is the type of the accusation that was correctly applied to Christ as the sin-bearer.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The specific false accusations &mdash; taking pledges from brothers for nothing, stripping naked the weary &mdash; contrast with Christ&rsquo;s actual works: he gave rather than took; he clothed the naked (the woman with the issue of blood found wholeness rather than shame). Luke 4:18 (&ldquo;he has sent me to proclaim release to the captives&rdquo;) is the programmatic reversal of Eliphaz&rsquo;s accusation against Job: where Eliphaz claims Job took from the poor, Christ&rsquo;s mission is to give to the poor.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Eliphaz&rsquo;s accusation that Job withheld water from the weary and bread from the hungry inverts Christ&rsquo;s actual ministry: John 4:10 (Jesus offers living water); John 6:35 (&ldquo;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst&rdquo;). The false accusation against Job that he denied water and bread is answered by Christ who gives the water and bread that fully satisfy.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The contrast between the powerful man who occupies the land and the widow/orphan who is pushed aside is reversed in Christ&rsquo;s kingdom: Matt 5:3 (&ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven&rdquo;); Luke 1:52&ndash;53 (&ldquo;he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate; he has filled the hungry with good things, and the rich he has sent away empty&rdquo;). The social structure that Eliphaz accuses Job of exploiting is precisely the structure Christ&rsquo;s kingdom overturns.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The widows sent away empty and orphans crushed &mdash; the paradigmatic crimes against the socially vulnerable &mdash; are the crimes Christ&rsquo;s entire ministry implicitly reverses. Matt 15:21&ndash;28 (the Syrophoenician widow&rsquo;s daughter healed); Mark 12:42&ndash;43 (the widow&rsquo;s offering honored above all). The widow who is sent away empty is, in Christ&rsquo;s ministry, the widow who is received and whose offering is celebrated. The orphan is the one to whom Christ says &ldquo;I will not leave you as orphans; I will come to you&rdquo; (John 14:18).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Snares surrounding Job because of his supposed wickedness &mdash; the retributive reading of suffering that the passion narrative definitively overturns. The snares and terrors at Gethsemane and Golgotha surrounded the only truly innocent person in history; the retributive reading would require that Christ was uniquely wicked. The absurdity of that conclusion reveals the absurdity of applying the snares-equals-wickedness formula to Job.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Darkness and floods overwhelming the wicked &mdash; the judgment categories that Eliphaz applies to Job. The darkness at the crucifixion (Matt 27:45: three hours of darkness) is the sign that judgment has indeed fallen &mdash; but on the innocent one who bore the guilty&rsquo;s penalty. The darkness that should not be Job&rsquo;s fell on Christ; Christ&rsquo;s darkness-free resurrection light is what Job will ultimately receive (the divine speeches and epilogue).</p>",
    "12": "<p>God high in the heavens, the stars at their height &mdash; Eliphaz describes divine transcendence to establish human smallness. Phil 2:6&ndash;7 reverses this vertically: the one who existed in the form of God (&ldquo;the heights of heaven&rdquo;) &ldquo;emptied himself, taking the form of a servant.&rdquo; The divine transcendence that Eliphaz uses to crush Job&rsquo;s legal pretensions is the height from which Christ voluntarily descended to be present in human suffering.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The charge that Job thinks God cannot see through the thick clouds &mdash; a theology of divine distance &mdash; is answered by the Incarnation: John 1:14 (&ldquo;the Word became flesh and dwelt among us&rdquo;). The God who Eliphaz describes as distant behind clouds is the God who in Christ came as close as possible, dwelling in the same flesh that Job inhabits. The divine hiddenness that Eliphaz uses as an argument becomes the divine nearness of the Incarnation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Thick clouds veil him, so that he does not see, and he walks on the vault of heaven.&rdquo; John 1:14: &ldquo;we have seen his glory.&rdquo; The cloud-veiled God is the God who unveiled himself in Christ: Col 1:15 (&ldquo;he is the image of the invisible God&rdquo;); John 14:9 (&ldquo;whoever has seen me has seen the Father&rdquo;). The invisibility that Eliphaz uses to dismiss Job&rsquo;s case is the very invisibility that the Incarnation permanently dissolves: God has become visible in the face of Christ (2 Cor 4:6).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The old path of the wicked who were swept away anticipates the NT teaching on the two ways: Matt 7:13&ndash;14 (the broad road leading to destruction and the narrow road leading to life). Christ is the narrow road itself (John 14:6: &ldquo;I am the way&rdquo;); those who choose the old path of the wicked choose the path that was judged in the flood and will be judged again at the eschaton.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The wicked snatched away before their time, their foundation poured out as a stream &mdash; the sudden collapse of those who built on the wrong foundation. Matt 7:24&ndash;27: the house on sand falls, the house on rock (Christ as the cornerstone, Eph 2:20) stands. The poured-out foundation of the wicked is the anti-type of Christ as the foundation that cannot be moved (1 Cor 3:11: &ldquo;no one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ&rdquo;).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The wicked saying &ldquo;depart from us&rdquo; to God anticipates the eschatological judgment: Matt 7:23 (&ldquo;depart from me, I never knew you&rdquo;). The direction of the &ldquo;depart&rdquo; is reversed: the wicked who said depart to God will hear &ldquo;depart&rdquo; from the Son of Man as judge. The demand to be left alone from God is granted eschatologically in a way that is the ultimate loss.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Yet God filled their houses with good things &mdash; the paradox of divine generosity toward those who reject him. Matt 5:45 (&ldquo;he makes his sun rise on the evil and on the good, and sends rain on the just and on the unjust&rdquo;): the common grace of divine goodness is extended even to those who say &ldquo;depart from us.&rdquo; This common grace is ultimately aimed at repentance (Rom 2:4: &ldquo;do you not know that God&rsquo;s kindness is meant to lead you to repentance?&rdquo;).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The righteous seeing and rejoicing at the wicked&rsquo;s judgment &mdash; the eschatological vindication of the innocent. Rev 19:1&ndash;3: the heavenly multitude cries &ldquo;Hallelujah! Salvation and glory and power belong to our God, for his judgments are true and just.&rdquo; The rejoicing of the righteous at divine judgment is not schadenfreude but the recognition that justice has finally been done &mdash; the vindication that Job has been longing for throughout the dialogue.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Their abundance destroyed and fire consuming their remnant &mdash; the complete judgment on those who rejected the divine offer. Heb 10:27: &ldquo;a fearful expectation of judgment, and a fury of fire that will consume the adversaries.&rdquo; The fire that consumes the remnant of the wicked is the same fire that purifies and refines the righteous (1 Cor 3:13&ndash;15: the fire that tests each one&rsquo;s work). Christ bore the consuming fire of divine judgment so that those who trust him are refined but not consumed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Agree with God and be at peace; thereby good will come to you&rdquo; &mdash; Eliphaz unknowingly describes the gospel: Rom 5:1 (&ldquo;since we have been justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ&rdquo;). The peace that Eliphaz offers through moral reform and submission, the NT offers through Christ&rsquo;s atoning work. The structure is the same (agree with God → peace); the mechanism is entirely different: not human penitential effort but Christ&rsquo;s righteousness credited to the believer.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Receiving instruction from God&rsquo;s mouth and placing his words in the heart &mdash; the Torah-internalization that Eliphaz recommends is the structure of the new covenant: Jer 31:33 (&ldquo;I will put my law within them, and I will write it on their hearts&rdquo;); Heb 8:10 (the new covenant promise fulfilled in Christ). The external law becomes internal by the Spirit; what Eliphaz prescribes as a human moral achievement, the new covenant delivers as divine gift through Christ.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;If you return to the Almighty you will be built up&rdquo; &mdash; Eliphaz&rsquo;s restoration formula. 1 Pet 2:5: &ldquo;you yourselves like living stones are being built up as a spiritual house.&rdquo; The building-up (<em>tibaneh</em>) that Eliphaz offers through repentance, the NT delivers through union with Christ as the cornerstone. The removal of iniquity from the tent is completed in Christ through forgiveness and the Spirit&rsquo;s sanctifying work.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Laying gold in the dust, treating Ophir gold as river-gravel &mdash; the detachment from wealth as the condition of genuine spiritual treasure. Matt 6:19&ndash;21 (&ldquo;do not lay up for yourselves treasures on earth&hellip;but lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven&rdquo;); Matt 13:44&ndash;46 (the man who sells all he has for the pearl of great value). Eliphaz calls for material detachment so that God becomes the treasure; Christ is the treasure for whom all earthly gold is gladly counted as refuse (Phil 3:8: &ldquo;I count everything as loss because of the surpassing worth of knowing Christ Jesus my Lord&rdquo;).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;Let the Almighty be your gold and your precious silver&rdquo; &mdash; God as the supreme treasure is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s highest aspiration (Ps 73:25: &ldquo;there is nothing on earth that I desire besides you&rdquo;). In the NT, this supreme treasure is located specifically in Christ: Col 2:3 (&ldquo;in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&rdquo;). The God-as-treasure that Eliphaz describes in abstract theological terms is identified concretely in Christ as the one in whom all divine treasure is found and accessible.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Delight in the Almighty and lifting the face to God &mdash; the restored intimacy of the forgiven. Heb 4:16: &ldquo;let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace, that we may receive mercy and find grace to help in time of need.&rdquo; The face lifted in confidence toward God is the access that Christ&rsquo;s high-priestly work makes possible; the delight that Eliphaz prescribes as the goal of human penitential effort, Christ provides as the fruit of accomplished redemption.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Prayer to God with the promise of being heard &mdash; Eliphaz&rsquo;s restoration promise. John 15:7: &ldquo;if you abide in me, and my words abide in you, ask whatever you wish, and it will be done for you.&rdquo; The conditions of heard prayer that Eliphaz describes (restored relationship, cleared conscience) are fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s work: 1 John 5:14 (&ldquo;this is the confidence that we have toward him, that if we ask anything according to his will he hears us&rdquo;). The hearing prayer that Eliphaz offers through moral performance, Christ delivers through union.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;You will decide on a matter and it will be established for you, and light will shine on your ways&rdquo; &mdash; the extraordinary promise of effective prayer and divine guidance. John 15:16: &ldquo;you did not choose me, but I chose you and appointed you that you should go and bear fruit, and so that whatever you ask the Father in my name, he may give it to you.&rdquo; The decree that stands is the prayer offered in Christ&rsquo;s name; the light on the ways is Christ himself who is the light (John 8:12: &ldquo;I am the light of the world; whoever follows me will not walk in darkness&rdquo;).</p>",
    "29": "<p>When others are humbled you will say &ldquo;there is lifting up,&rdquo; for God saves the humble &mdash; the reversal of the proud. Luke 14:11: &ldquo;everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, and he who humbles himself will be exalted.&rdquo; Jas 4:6 (&ldquo;God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble,&rdquo; quoting Prov 3:34). This principle, which Eliphaz uses as the moral framework for Job&rsquo;s restoration, is fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s humiliation and exaltation (Phil 2:8&ndash;9: &ldquo;he humbled himself&hellip;therefore God has highly exalted him&rdquo;).</p>",
    "30": "<p>The innocent man delivered through the cleanness of Job&rsquo;s hands &mdash; the intercessory function of the righteous. The ironically profound concluding verse of Eliphaz&rsquo;s speech prefigures precisely what happens in the epilogue (42:7&ndash;8): God commands the friends to go to Job, and Job will pray for them. Christ&rsquo;s clean hands &mdash; his perfect righteousness &mdash; are the ground of intercession for the guilty (Heb 7:25: &ldquo;he always lives to make intercession for them&rdquo;). The innocent man whose clean hands deliver the guilty is the pattern of Christ&rsquo;s substitutionary intercession.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>Job&rsquo;s response to Eliphaz does not directly refute the specific accusations but intensifies the demand for a direct divine encounter. The legal framing (&ldquo;my complaint is bitter&rdquo; &mdash; a formal legal claim) heightens rather than resolves the tension. In the NT, Jesus takes the legal approach from the opposite direction: he does not demand an audience with God but is God granting the audience; in Heb 4:16, the invitation is the reverse of Job&rsquo;s demand: &ldquo;let us approach the throne of grace with confidence.&rdquo;</p>",
    "2": "<p>My complaint is bitter; his hand is heavy despite my groaning &mdash; the unrelieved weight of divine dealing. Heb 12:11: &ldquo;for the moment all discipline seems painful rather than pleasant, but later it yields the peaceful fruit of righteousness to those who have been trained by it.&rdquo; The heavy hand that Job feels, the NT reframes as the Father&rsquo;s discipline for those he loves (Heb 12:6&ndash;7). The present heaviness does not negate the future fruit.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Oh, that I knew where I might find him&rdquo; &mdash; one of the greatest expressions of spiritual longing in the OT. John 14:6: &ldquo;I am the way, the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me.&rdquo; The answer to Job&rsquo;s longing to find God and come to his dwelling place is the Incarnation: &ldquo;the Word became flesh and dwelt among us&rdquo; (John 1:14). Christ did not just show the way to God; he is the way, the accessible presence of God.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;I would lay my case before him and fill my mouth with arguments&rdquo; &mdash; Job&rsquo;s longing for direct legal access to God. Heb 9:24: &ldquo;Christ has entered not into holy places made with hands, which are copies of the true things, but into heaven itself, now to appear in the presence of God on our behalf.&rdquo; Job longs to appear before God and argue his case; Christ appears before God on behalf of those who trust him &mdash; not to argue their case but to present his finished work as the complete answer to every charge.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Job&rsquo;s confidence that God&rsquo;s words to him would vindicate rather than condemn anticipates the assurance of those who are in Christ: Rom 8:1 (&ldquo;there is therefore now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus&rdquo;). The hearing Job hopes will vindicate him is the hearing that Christ&rsquo;s atonement guarantees for those who are found in him; the divine answer that Job expects to be favorable is the favorable verdict of justification.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The hope that God would not press his case with great power but only pay attention to the legal merits reflects Job&rsquo;s awareness of the power imbalance. In Christ, the power imbalance is resolved by the mediator who bridges both sides: 1 Tim 2:5 (&ldquo;there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus&rdquo;). The mediator who knows both the divine and human sides of the case is uniquely capable of the equitable legal engagement Job hopes for.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;There an upright man could argue with him, and I would be acquitted forever by my judge&rdquo; &mdash; the hoped-for permanent acquittal. Rom 8:33&ndash;34: &ldquo;who shall bring any charge against God&rsquo;s elect? It is God who justifies. Who is to condemn? Christ Jesus is the one who died &mdash; more than that, who was raised &mdash; who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us.&rdquo; The permanent acquittal Job longs for is the definitive justification that Christ&rsquo;s resurrection and intercession guarantee.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The four-directional search for God &mdash; forward, backward, left, right &mdash; finds God nowhere. Col 1:15: &ldquo;he is the image of the invisible God.&rdquo; The invisible God whom no spatial search can locate became visible, locatable, touchable in Christ (1 John 1:1: &ldquo;that which we have heard, which we have seen with our eyes, which we looked upon and have touched with our hands, concerning the word of life&rdquo;). The one who cannot be found by spatial search came and found us.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Searching north, south &mdash; not perceiving him. Acts 17:27: Paul describes the nations searching for God, &ldquo;though he is actually not far from each one of us.&rdquo; The hiddenness of God that makes Job&rsquo;s four-directional search futile is the hiddenness that the Incarnation permanently transforms: &ldquo;behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel (which means, God with us)&rdquo; (Matt 1:23). The God who eluded Job&rsquo;s search in all four directions became &ldquo;God with us.&rdquo;</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;But he knows the way that I take; when he has tested me, I will come out as gold&rdquo; &mdash; one of Job&rsquo;s most confident expressions of faith through testing. 1 Pet 1:6&ndash;7: &ldquo;in this you rejoice, though now for a little while, if necessary, you have been grieved by various trials, so that the tested genuineness of your faith &mdash; more precious than gold that perishes though it is tested by fire &mdash; may be found to result in praise and glory and honor at the revelation of Jesus Christ.&rdquo; Job&rsquo;s gold-trial typology is the exact metaphor Peter applies to the faith-testing of Christians.</p>",
    "11": "<p>My foot has held fast to his steps; I have kept his way and have not turned aside &mdash; the perseverance of the righteous on the appointed path. Heb 12:1&ndash;2: &ldquo;let us run with endurance the race that is set before us, looking to Jesus, the founder and perfecter of our faith, who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross.&rdquo; The one who held fast to God&rsquo;s steps without turning aside is the pattern; Christ is the ultimate fulfillment &mdash; the one who ran the full race without deviation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Treasuring the words of God&rsquo;s mouth more than appointed food &mdash; the divine word as superior to physical sustenance. Matt 4:4: &ldquo;man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that comes from the mouth of God&rdquo; (quoting Deut 8:3). Christ spoke this principle against the tempter during his own wilderness fast; he lived it through his entire ministry; and he became it: &ldquo;I am the bread of life&rdquo; (John 6:35) &mdash; the word of God that is itself the living bread.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;But he is unchangeable, and who can turn him back?&rdquo; &mdash; the immutability of the divine plan. Heb 13:8: &ldquo;Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever.&rdquo; Jas 1:17: &ldquo;every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, with whom there is no variation or shadow due to change.&rdquo; The unchangeability that terrifies Job is the unchangeability of the one who has committed to his eternal covenant in Christ: his plan to redeem cannot be turned back.</p>",
    "14": "<p>God completing his decree against Job &mdash; the sovereign divine plan carried through. Acts 2:23: &ldquo;this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God.&rdquo; The divine decree that feels to Job like relentless divine determination against him is, in the NT, the relentless divine determination for human redemption, expressed supremely in the cross. The &ldquo;many such things&rdquo; that God has decreed include the passion, resurrection, and restoration of all who are in Christ.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Being terrified at God&rsquo;s presence, dismayed when considering him &mdash; the overwhelming awe of divine encounter. Rev 1:17: John the Apostle falls at Christ&rsquo;s feet as though dead at the vision of the risen Christ &mdash; and Christ lays his right hand on him and says, &ldquo;Fear not, I am the first and the last, and the living one.&rdquo; The terror of divine encounter is real; Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;fear not&rdquo; is the specific word that transforms the encounter from annihilating dread to life-giving meeting.</p>",
    "16": "<p>God making Job&rsquo;s heart faint, the Almighty terrifying him &mdash; the divine action that produces the deepest dread. Luke 22:41&ndash;44: Christ&rsquo;s sweat like drops of blood in Gethsemane is the most extreme example of a heart made faint by divine dealing. The one who experienced the fullest measure of the terror that Job describes is Christ facing the cup of divine wrath; having drunk it, he could say &ldquo;let not your hearts be troubled&rdquo; (John 14:1) to those who trust in his completed work.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Job not silenced by darkness or by the thick darkness that covers his face &mdash; the persistence of faith through darkness. Rom 8:35&ndash;37: &ldquo;who shall separate us from the love of Christ? Shall tribulation, or distress, or persecution, or famine, or nakedness, or danger, or sword? &hellip; No, in all these things we are more than conquerors through him who loved us.&rdquo; Job&rsquo;s refusal to be silenced by darkness is the OT anticipation of the &ldquo;more than conquerors&rdquo; confidence of those who know that nothing can separate them from Christ&rsquo;s love.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;Why are times not kept by the Almighty?&rdquo; &mdash; Job&rsquo;s demand for divine scheduling of justice. 2 Pet 3:8&ndash;9: &ldquo;with the Lord one day is as a thousand years, and a thousand years as one day. The Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise as some count slowness, but is patient toward you, not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance.&rdquo; The delay of justice that Job finds incomprehensible is the patience of God aimed at repentance; Rev 22:12: &ldquo;behold, I am coming soon.&rdquo; The &ldquo;times&rdquo; are set; Christ returns on the Father&rsquo;s schedule.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Moving boundary stones &mdash; the paradigmatic social crime of the ancient world. In the NT, this crime&rsquo;s spiritual analog is teaching that moves the eternal boundaries of God&rsquo;s moral law: Matt 5:17 (&ldquo;do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them&rdquo;). Christ is the one who honors and fulfills the permanent boundaries of God&rsquo;s law, while the one who moves those boundaries is under judgment (Gal 1:8&ndash;9).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Stealing the widow&rsquo;s ox and the orphan&rsquo;s donkey &mdash; predatory exploitation of the vulnerable. The Incarnation&rsquo;s specific social context: Jesus was born into poverty (Luke 2:7), lived as a craftsman&rsquo;s son, associated deliberately with the poor and marginalized. The one who was himself socially marginal (no permanent home, Matt 8:20; executed between criminals) is the countertype to the predator who steals from the widow and orphan.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The poor of the earth hiding together from oppression &mdash; the underground existence of the dispossessed. Jesus&rsquo; beatitude: &ldquo;blessed are the meek (<em>praeis</em>, the poor and dispossessed), for they shall inherit the earth&rdquo; (Matt 5:5). The poor who hide now will receive the inheritance; the eschatological reversal of Job 24 is the full kingdom that Christ inaugurates and will consummate.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The dispossessed poor like wild donkeys foraging in the wilderness &mdash; marginal existence outside the structures of social security. The wilderness was also where Jesus was tested (Matt 4:1&ndash;11), where the disciples were sent (Mark 6:31&ndash;32 for rest), and where John the Baptist proclaimed the way of the Lord (Luke 3:4). The wild-donkey existence of the marginalized is the world Christ deliberately entered in his incarnation and ministry.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Gathering fodder in another&rsquo;s field, gleaning in the vineyard of the wicked &mdash; the survival economics of the dispossessed. Ruth gleaned in Boaz&rsquo;s field (Ruth 2); Jesus&rsquo; disciples plucked grain on the Sabbath because they were hungry (Matt 12:1). The gleaner in another&rsquo;s field is the economic precarity that the kingdom of God will transform: the kingdom feast where all are invited and all eat until satisfied (Matt 22:9&ndash;10; Luke 14:21&ndash;23).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The naked sleeping without clothing through the night, with no covering in the cold &mdash; material deprivation that fails human dignity. Matt 25:36,38: &ldquo;I was naked and you clothed me.&rdquo; The eschatological judgment turns on how the community treated the naked: in serving the naked, they served Christ himself. The naked who have no covering are precisely the ones in whom Christ says he was present; clothing them is clothing him.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Wet with mountain rains, clinging to the rock for want of shelter &mdash; exposure without protection. The rock as the only available shelter for the destitute is the theological image of God as rock (Ps 18:2; 31:3; 62:2). Christ became the permanent shelter for the spiritually destitute: &ldquo;he who dwells in the shelter of the Most High will abide in the shadow of the Almighty&rdquo; (Ps 91:1); Rev 7:16: &ldquo;they shall hunger no more, neither thirst any more; the sun shall not strike them, nor any scorching heat.&rdquo;</p>",
    "9": "<p>Orphans snatched from the breast, infants of the poor taken as pledges &mdash; child exploitation for debt. The Christ who said &ldquo;let the little children come to me and do not hinder them, for to such belongs the kingdom of heaven&rdquo; (Matt 19:14) is the one who specifically protects and receives those whom the economic system exploits. The children snatched for debt are the countertype of the children welcomed to the kingdom.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Going about naked, hungry, carrying the sheaves of grain they produce but cannot eat &mdash; the exploitation economy where workers starve amid their own production. The Lord&rsquo;s Supper specifically addresses this inversion: 1 Cor 11:21 (the rich eat and drink while the poor go hungry at the same table). Christ&rsquo;s institution of the common meal is the specific counter to the economic inversion Job describes.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Treading winepresses while thirsty &mdash; producing abundance while experiencing deprivation. John 4:13&ndash;14: &ldquo;everyone who drinks of this water will be thirsty again, but whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again.&rdquo; The workers who tread wine while thirsty find their thirst permanently satisfied in Christ; he who said &ldquo;I thirst&rdquo; from the cross (John 19:28) bore the thirst so that those who come to him need never thirst again.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;From the city the dying groan, and the soul of the wounded cries for help; yet God charges no one with wrongdoing&rdquo; &mdash; the cry of the oppressed without divine response. Luke 18:7&ndash;8: &ldquo;will not God give justice to his elect who cry to him day and night? Will he delay long over them? I tell you, he will give justice to them speedily.&rdquo; The cry that appears unanswered in Job 24:12 receives Christ&rsquo;s direct promise: the divine response is coming speedily. The apparent divine indifference is the patience before the eschatological judgment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Those who rebel against the light &mdash; the moral taxonomy of light-haters. John 3:19&ndash;20: &ldquo;people loved the darkness rather than the light because their works were evil. For everyone who does wicked things hates the light and does not come to the light, lest his works should be exposed.&rdquo; The light-rebelling wicked of Job 24:13 are precisely the ones who flee the light of Christ; the darkness they prefer is the darkness from which Christ has come to deliver them (1 Pet 2:9: &ldquo;called out of darkness into his marvelous light&rdquo;).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The murderer rising at dawn to kill the poor &mdash; the exploitation of the transitional moment. Christ&rsquo;s resurrection at dawn (John 20:1: &ldquo;early on the first day of the week, while it was still dark&rdquo;) is the ultimate transformation of the dawn: the time when the murderer rises to kill becomes the time when the Life-giver rises from death. The darkness that was the murderer&rsquo;s ally is permanently defeated by the light of resurrection dawn.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The adulterer waiting for twilight &mdash; the moral coding of darkness as concealment. Eph 5:11&ndash;13: &ldquo;take no part in the unfruitful works of darkness, but instead expose them. For it is shameful even to speak of the things that they do in secret. But when anything is exposed by the light, it becomes visible.&rdquo; Christ as the light that exposes darkness (John 3:20&ndash;21) is the specific answer to the darkness-hiding that the adulterer practices: nothing is hidden from the one who is the light of the world.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The thief sealing himself in darkness, not knowing the light &mdash; the complete severance from the light. 1 Thess 5:4&ndash;5: &ldquo;but you are not in darkness, brothers, for that day to surprise you like a thief. For you are all children of light, children of the day. We are not of the night or of the darkness.&rdquo; Christ transforms his followers from darkness-children into light-children; the thief who seals himself in darkness is the anti-type of the community that has been transferred from darkness&rsquo; dominion to the kingdom of light (Col 1:13).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Thick darkness as morning to the light-haters &mdash; the complete inversion of the diurnal moral order. At the crucifixion, the moral inversion reached its maximum: darkness at noon (Matt 27:45), the Light of the World extinguished in apparent defeat. But the Easter morning reversed this: darkness became dawn, death became life. The permanent inversion that the wicked inhabit was temporarily entered by Christ and definitively overturned.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The wicked swift on the water&rsquo;s surface, their portion cursed in the land &mdash; the lightness of the wicked who have no substantial root. John 15:6: &ldquo;whoever does not abide in me is thrown away like a branch and withers.&rdquo; The rootless wicked who skim the surface are the anti-type of those who abide in Christ, the true Vine, and draw sustenance from his life.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Drought and heat consuming the snow waters, Sheol taking those who have sinned &mdash; the irreversible movement of the unrooted toward death. 1 Cor 15:55&ndash;57: &ldquo;O death, where is your victory? O death, where is your sting? The sting of death is sin, and the power of sin is the law. But thanks be to God, who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.&rdquo; The Sheol-consumption that is the end of the sinner is defeated by Christ&rsquo;s death and resurrection; the sting is removed for those who are his.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The womb forgotten, worms feasting on them, no longer remembered &mdash; the complete extinction. Heb 11:4: &ldquo;through his faith, though he died, he still speaks.&rdquo; The righteous are remembered; the wicked&rsquo;s memory perishes. Christ&rsquo;s name is eternal: Phil 2:9&ndash;10 (&ldquo;the name that is above every name&rdquo;). The worm-eaten forgotten dead are the anti-type of the one who rose bodily and will never see corruption.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Exploiting the barren woman and withholding good from the widow &mdash; cruelty to the reproductively marginal. The barren who conceives by divine action is a repeated OT type: Sarah, Rebekah, Rachel, Hannah &mdash; all barren until God opens the womb. The church, described as the barren woman who now has more children than the married (Isa 54:1, quoted in Gal 4:27), is the ultimate fulfillment: those who had no covenant-status become the family of God through Christ.</p>",
    "22": "<p>God dragging the mighty by his power &mdash; the sovereign reversal of human strength. Isa 40:29&ndash;31: &ldquo;he gives power to the faint, and to him who has no might he increases strength.&rdquo; 1 Cor 1:27: &ldquo;God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong.&rdquo; The dragging-down of the mighty is the same reversal as the Magnificat (Luke 1:52: &ldquo;he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate&rdquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>God giving the wicked security while his eyes watch their ways &mdash; the patience of divine watching before judgment. Acts 17:30: &ldquo;the times of ignorance God overlooked, but now he commands all people everywhere to repent, because he has fixed a day on which he will judge the world in righteousness by a man whom he has appointed.&rdquo; The divine watching that Job observes is the watching before the appointed judgment; the appointed judge is Christ (Acts 17:31).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The wicked exalted for a little while then gone, cut down like heads of grain &mdash; the temporary nature of wickedness&rsquo; apparent triumph. Rev 20:10: &ldquo;the devil who had deceived them was thrown into the lake of fire and sulfur.&rdquo; The brief exaltation of the wicked &mdash; which seems permanent to those who suffer under it &mdash; is temporary in the divine perspective. The &ldquo;little while&rdquo; of the wicked&rsquo;s triumph ends at the parousia of Christ, the one appointed to judge.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Job&rsquo;s challenge: who can prove him a liar? The ultimate answer is no one, because Job correctly diagnoses both his own innocence and the empirical reality of unequal divine dealing with the righteous and wicked. In the NT, this is not resolved by argument but by eschatological promise: Rev 22:12 (&ldquo;I am coming soon, bringing my recompense with me&rdquo;). The recompense that Christ brings finally vindicates every Job who suffered innocently and every Eliphaz who misapplied the retributive formula.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>Bildad&rsquo;s third and shortest speech (6 verses) reflects the exhaustion of the friends&rsquo; theological resources. Despite its brevity, it asks the most important question in the book: how can a human being be righteous before God? In the NT this question is not dismissed but fully answered in Christ: Rom 3:21&ndash;26 (the righteousness of God through faith in Christ); 2 Cor 5:21 (&ldquo;he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&rdquo;).</p>",
    "2": "<p>God&rsquo;s dominion and awesome power making peace in the heights &mdash; the sovereign peace of the divine order. Col 1:19&ndash;20: &ldquo;in him all the fullness of God was pleased to dwell, and through him to reconcile to himself all things, whether on earth or in heaven, making peace by the blood of his cross.&rdquo; The divine peace in the heights that Bildad describes abstractly is the peace that Christ accomplished concretely &mdash; the reconciliation of all things through the cross, including the heavenly realm.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The innumerable armies of God &mdash; the unlimited divine power. Heb 1:6: &ldquo;let all God&rsquo;s angels worship him&rdquo; (Christ, at his entrance into the world). Matt 26:53: Jesus at his arrest: &ldquo;do you think that I cannot appeal to my Father, and he will at once send me more than twelve legions of angels?&rdquo; The unlimited divine armies that Bildad invokes as evidence of human smallness are the armies that stood at Christ&rsquo;s disposal and which he refused to summon in order to accomplish redemption by a different means.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;How then can man be righteous before God? How can he who is born of woman be pure?&rdquo; &mdash; the question the Incarnation answers. Rom 3:21&ndash;22: &ldquo;the righteousness of God through faith in Jesus Christ for all who believe.&rdquo; Gal 4:4: &ldquo;born of woman, born under the law, to redeem those under the law, so that we might receive adoption as sons.&rdquo; The &ldquo;born of woman&rdquo; who is pure is Christ; and those united to him receive his purity credited to them.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Even the moon is not bright and the stars are not pure in God&rsquo;s eyes &mdash; the cosmic purity hierarchy. Rev 21:23: &ldquo;the city has no need of sun or moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it light, and its lamp is the Lamb.&rdquo; The moon and stars whose light falls short of divine purity will be superseded by the light of Christ himself as the lamp of the new creation. The hierarchy of brightness reaches its summit not in the stars but in the Lamb whose glory outshines them all.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;How much less man, who is a maggot, and the son of man, who is a worm!&rdquo; &mdash; the nadir of human worth before divine holiness. Ps 22:6: &ldquo;I am a worm and not a man&rdquo; &mdash; the suffering righteous one&rsquo;s self-description in the paradigmatic passion psalm. Col 1:15: &ldquo;he is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn of all creation.&rdquo; The worm-son-of-man is the one whom Ps 22:6 anticipates and who is identified with the divine image and firstborn of creation. The maximum creaturely humility (&ldquo;worm&rdquo;) and the maximum creaturely dignity (&ldquo;image of God&rdquo;) meet in Christ.</p>"
  },
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>Job&rsquo;s sarcastic response &mdash; &ldquo;how you have helped him who has no power!&rdquo; &mdash; demolishes the friends&rsquo; practical futility. In contrast, Christ&rsquo;s help to those with no power is actual: Heb 2:18 (&ldquo;because he himself has suffered when tempted, he is able to help those who are being tempted&rdquo;); Heb 4:15 (&ldquo;we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses&rdquo;). The help that the friends could not supply, Christ supplies by entering the weakness himself.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Job&rsquo;s sarcasm continues: you have saved the arm with no strength! The irony in the NT is that Christ does exactly this &mdash; not through the superior power of human counsel but through weakness: 1 Cor 1:25 (&ldquo;the weakness of God is stronger than men&rdquo;); 2 Cor 12:9 (&ldquo;my power is made perfect in weakness&rdquo;). The salvation of the arm with no strength is the specific form divine power takes in the cross.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Counsel to the one without wisdom &mdash; the genuine counsel that the friends claimed to offer but could not supply. 1 Cor 1:30: &ldquo;Christ Jesus, who has become for us wisdom from God.&rdquo; Col 2:3: &ldquo;in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge.&rdquo; The wisdom the friends lacked and could not provide, Christ is and provides: the Wisdom of God incarnate who is the answer to every wisdom question the book of Job poses.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Job challenges whose breath has spoken through Bildad &mdash; the question of the source of authoritative speech. John 16:13: &ldquo;when the Spirit of truth comes, he will guide you into all the truth, for he will not speak on his own authority, but whatever he hears he will speak.&rdquo; The breath of God (the Spirit) that did not speak through Bildad speaks through Christ and through the Spirit he sends; the authoritative divine voice that the friends lacked was the voice of the Spirit whom Christ would pour out.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Rephaim trembling under the waters &mdash; even the dead dread the divine. Matt 8:29: the demons cry out to Jesus, &ldquo;have you come here to torment us before the time?&rdquo; &mdash; they know the appointed judge. Rev 1:18: &ldquo;I died, and behold I am alive forevermore, and I have the keys of Death and Hades.&rdquo; The Rephaim who tremble before God in Job 26:5 tremble before Christ as the one who has the keys of Hades.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Sheol naked before God, Abaddon uncovered &mdash; no realm outside divine visibility. Heb 4:13: &ldquo;nothing in all creation is hidden from God&rsquo;s sight; everything is uncovered and laid bare before the eyes of him to whom we must give account.&rdquo; Rev 9:11 names Abaddon as the angel of the bottomless pit; Rev 20:14: &ldquo;Death and Hades were thrown into the lake of fire.&rdquo; The naked transparency of Sheol before God is the transparency before Christ who holds authority over Death and Hades.</p>",
    "7": "<p>God stretching out the north over the void, hanging the earth on nothing &mdash; the cosmic sovereignty of the Creator. Col 1:16&ndash;17: &ldquo;by him all things were created, in heaven and on earth, visible and invisible, whether thrones or dominions or rulers or authorities &mdash; all things were created through him and for him. And he is before all things, and in him all things hold together.&rdquo; The earth hanging on nothing is held in place by Christ&rsquo;s sustaining word (Heb 1:3: &ldquo;upholding the universe by the word of his power&rdquo;).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The waters bound in the clouds, the cloud not splitting &mdash; the divine management of creation&rsquo;s physical systems. John 1:3: &ldquo;all things were made through him, and without him was not any thing made that was made.&rdquo; The bound waters and the intact cloud are among the &ldquo;all things&rdquo; created and sustained by Christ the Word. The intricate ecological systems that Job marvels at are held together by the same one who took on flesh in the stable at Bethlehem.</p>",
    "9": "<p>God covering the face of his throne, spreading his cloud over it &mdash; the veiling of the divine throne. Heb 4:14&ndash;16: we have a great high priest who has passed through the heavens &mdash; Christ Jesus; therefore approach the throne of grace with confidence. The throne veiled in cloud that the high priest could only approach once a year through layers of ritual protection is the throne that Christ has opened permanently for those in him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The circle inscribed on the face of the waters as the boundary between light and darkness &mdash; the divine ordering of the created world. Gen 1:3&ndash;4: God separating light from darkness was the first creative act. John 1:4&ndash;5: &ldquo;in him was life, and the life was the light of men. The light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it.&rdquo; The boundary between light and darkness that God inscribed at creation is the boundary that Christ&rsquo;s resurrection permanently establishes: the darkness cannot overcome the light.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The pillars of heaven trembling at God&rsquo;s rebuke &mdash; the cosmic structures responding to divine authority. Matt 8:27: the disciples at the stilled storm: &ldquo;what sort of man is this, that even winds and sea obey him?&rdquo; The pillars of heaven that tremble at divine rebuke are the same forces that obey Christ&rsquo;s voice when he rebukes the wind and sea. The sovereign authority over creation that Job&rsquo;s hymn attributes to God is demonstrated in Christ&rsquo;s miraculous authority over natural forces.</p>",
    "12": "<p>God stilling the sea and striking down Rahab by his understanding &mdash; the creative defeat of the chaos-monster. Rev 21:1: &ldquo;then I saw a new heaven and a new earth, for the first heaven and the first earth had passed away, and the sea was no more.&rdquo; The sea whose chaos-principle God struck down in Rahab is the sea that no longer exists in the new creation; the chaotic principle that threatened ordered existence is permanently defeated. Christ&rsquo;s resurrection is the firstfruits of this new creation (1 Cor 15:20).</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;By his breath the skies were cleared; his hand pierced the fleeing serpent&rdquo; &mdash; the Spirit&rsquo;s action and the defeat of the chaos-serpent. Gen 3:15: the enmity between the serpent and the woman&rsquo;s seed, whose heel would be struck but who would crush the serpent&rsquo;s head. Col 2:15: &ldquo;he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him&rdquo; &mdash; the cross as the piercing of the ancient serpent. The fleeing serpent that God&rsquo;s hand pierced in creation is the serpent defeated at Calvary.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;These are but the outer fringes of his works; how faint the whisper we hear of him!&rdquo; &mdash; the epistemological humility before the vast incomprehensibility of God. 1 Cor 2:9: &ldquo;no eye has seen, nor ear heard, nor the heart of man imagined, what God has prepared for those who love him.&rdquo; 1 Cor 13:12: &ldquo;now I know in part; then I shall know fully, even as I have been fully known.&rdquo; The outer fringes that Job describes are the limit of present knowledge; the full knowledge awaits the face-to-face vision of Christ in the age to come.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'job')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'job', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CHRIST.values())
    parts = ', '.join(f'ch{ch}={len(CHRIST[ch])}' for ch in sorted(CHRIST, key=int))
    print(f'Job 22-26 mkt-christ: {total} verses written ({parts}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
